{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a25e1ee-72c2-4b69-bd85-34f62e8ff537","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and requires no extra install beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds example)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events (GC, kernel, I/O) beyond just CPU |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check — `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` shows CPU %, GC, threadpool in real time |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Deep kernel + user-mode tracing with full call stacks |\n\n**Tip:** Before tracing, run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm the CPU is actually in your app (vs. GC pressure or threadpool starvation) — it'll steer your investigation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"be067759-bf8c-4aec-8d22-e720b0b3a728","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":379},"id":"c4d85550-3b6a-49ed-9cb0-395b43226422","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:51:35.447Z","parentId":"7a2a8de3-2f00-454c-a5a7-4c256586f9e4"}
